A 'Larus occidentalis' is a species of seabird commonly known as the Western Gull.
It has a mostly white plumage with grey wings and black primaries.
Its bill is yellow with a red spot near the tip and the eyes are light yellow.
It has a robust body, a hooked beak and webbed feet.
They are commonly found along the western coast of North America, from Alaska to Mexico.
Their diet includes fish, invertebrates, eggs, and garbage.
They are a common sight in coastal areas and can often be seen perched on rocks or flying over the ocean.
